<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08044k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08044k">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08044k"> 44(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> leaning / sinuous</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Dans l&apos;autographe suivant, d&apos;un gar&ccedil;on de 10 ans, menteur par inconsistance, fig. 146, on observe la discordance des mouvements et des dimensions. &hellip; L&apos;inclinaison est trop grande et repr&eacute;sente un mouvement paresseux, l&apos;&eacute;criture est sinueuse et sans relief, les <i>t</i> sont &agrave; peine barr&eacute;s, les finales courtes, tous signes de d&eacute;bilit&eacute; et de fausset&eacute; qui s&apos;accordent tr&egrave;s bien pour provoquer le mensonge. <br><font color="green">[In the following autograph of a ten-year-old boy, a liar through inconsistency, fig. 146, we observe the disharmony between movement and dimension. [&hellip;]</font> The leaning slope is exaggerated and represents a lazy movement, the writing is sinuous and without depth, the <i>t</i>&apos;s are hardly crossed, the final strokes short, all indicative of idiocy and duplicity, both working together well to bring about a lie.] <small> J Cr&eacute;pieux-Jamin, <a name="JCJL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JCJL"><cite title="source">Les &eacute;l&eacute;ments de l'&eacute;criture des canailles</cite></a> (1923) 264</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
